'''Philip Sydney Smyth''' (14 March 1715 – 29 April 1787<ref name="ild4055"/>) was a [[Church of Ireland]] clergyman and fourth [[Viscount Strangford]] in the [[Peerage of Ireland]].<ref name="Brady1863" /> He succeeded to the viscountcy on 8 September 1724.<ref name="ild4055">{{cite web|url=http://www.qub.ac.uk/ild/?func=name_search&search=true&name_search_string=4055|title=Name 4055: Philip  Smyth|work=Irish Legislation Database|publisher=Queen's University Belfast|accessdate=16 June 2017}}</ref> King [[George II of Great Britain|George II]]  appointed him [[Dean of St. Patrick's Cathedral, Dublin]] in 1746 but the [[Cathedral chapter|chapter]] successfully argued that [[the Crown]] was not the patron, and he was dispossessed.<ref>Cotton 1849 [https://books.google.com/books?id=sJYAAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA334 p.334]</ref> He was successively [[precentor]] of [[Diocese of Elphin|Elphin]] (1746–52),  [[Dean of Derry]] (1752–69) and [[Archdeacon of Derry]] (1769–74).<ref>{{cite book|last=Cotton|first=Henry|title=Fasti Ecclesiæ Hibernicæ: The Succession of the Prelates and Members of the Cathedral Bodies in Ireland|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5j2drkk_pFoC&pg=PA138|accessdate=15 June 2017|year=1850|publisher=Hodges and Smith|volume=Vol.4: Connaught|page=138}}</ref><ref name="Brady1863">{{cite book|last=Brady|first=William Maziere|title=Clerical and parochial records of Cork, Cloyne, and Ross|chapterurl=https://archive.org/stream/clericalparochia01dubl#page/155|volume=Vol.1|year=1863|publisher=Printed for the author by A. Thom|location=Dublin|pages=155–156|chapter=Killaspugmullane}}</ref><ref>Cotton 1849 [https://books.google.com/books?id=sJYAAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA338 p.338]</ref>  He sat in the [[Irish House of Lords]] until 1784, when he was excluded by Act of Parliament after being tried and convicted of corruption for soliciting a bribe of £200 from the applicant in a court case that was pending before the House.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.qub.ac.uk/ild/?func=display_bill&id=3401|title=23 & 24 George III c.59: An Act for disabling Philip, Lord Viscount Strangford, from sitting in parliament or making any proxy therein, and also from sitting and voting on the trial of any peer.|work=Irish Legislation Database|accessdate=15 June 2017}}</ref><ref name="Howell1817">{{cite book|last=Howell|first=Thomas Bayly|title=A Complete Collection of State Trials and Proceedings for High Treason and Other Crimes and Misdemeanors |volume=22 |chapterurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=iKUrAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA161|accessdate=15 June 2017 |year=1817 |publisher=T. C. Hansard for Longman, Hurst, Rees, Orme, and Brown |pages=161–176 |chapter=569. Proceedings against Philip Lord Viscount Strangford for acting criminally and corruptly as a Lord of Parliament in Ireland }}</ref> The scandal was exacerbated by the fact that the it came less than two years after [[Repeal of Act for Securing Dependence of Ireland Act 1782|the Irish Lords had regained]] final [[appellate jurisdiction]] from the [[British House of Lords]].<ref name="DicksonGráda2003">{{cite book|last1=Dickson|first1=David|last2=Ó Gráda|first2=Cormac|title=Refiguring Ireland: Essays in Honour of L.M. Cullen|year=2003|publisher=Lilliput Press|isbn=9781901866841|page=197}}</ref>

==Family==
In 1741 Strangford married Mary, daughter of [[Anthony Jephson]],  [[Mallow (Parliament of Ireland constituency)|MP for Mallow]] and his second wife Hannah Rogerson. They had six children: Mary-Anne (1745–1823) and Anne-Philippa (1749–1830), both unmarried; Robert, Philip, and Frances, who all died young; and finally Lionel (1753–1801), who also took holy orders before succeeding as 5th Viscount.<ref name="Brady1863" /><ref>{{cite book|title=Debrett's Genealogical Peerage of Great Britain and Ireland|chapterurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=m19HAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA716|year=1847|publisher=William Pickering|page=716|chapter=Strangford}}</ref>

