{{infobox ethnic group |group= Reddiar |total = 700,000 |regions={{flag|India}} |rels= [[Hinduism]] |langs=[[Tamil language|Tamil]] |related=[[Reddy]], [[Kapu]] }}
'''Reddiar''' (also spelt as '''Reddiyar)''' is a [[Telugu language|Telugu]] speaking caste title of farming and mercantile [[social group]] of [[Tamil Nadu]], [[Kerala]] and [[Sri Lanka]].
Reddiars, [[Reddy]], Reddappa are considered and believed to come from the same origins and they spread across the lands of Southern and [[Central India]]. Political scientist [[Christophe Jaffrelot]] notes that, Reddiyars are the landlord caste originated from Telugu Country<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=tDN0MinxMigC&pg=PA447&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Rise of the Plebeians?: The Changing Face of the Indian Legislative Assemblies|last=Jaffrelot|first=Christophe|last2=Kumar|first2=Sanjay|date=2012-05-04|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781136516610|language=en}}</ref> and said they are patrons/Financial supporters of local temples in Tamil Region. The origin of the Reddys (Reddiars) has been linked to the Rashtrakutas and till date the Reddys in India are spread across the same area of Rasthrakuta dynasty, although opinions vary. The names have been believed to be derived according to the regions they are spread across. Reddy ayyagaru(iygaru-Head) in AndhraPradesh and Telangana, Reddiar (Reddy+ar)in Tamil Nadu and Kerala. Reddie, Reddappa (Reddy + appa- signifying respect) in Karnataka and Rayalaseema.
The Panta Reddiars, The Kanjam Reddiars, The Muduguveraya Reddiars moved from Andhra region in the search of rich black soil regions for cultivation and settled near Pondicherry. (In People of India/Indian Communities, Oxford University Press).
The Migration of the Reddys/Reddiars to areas of Chennai, Kanchipuram, Vellore and Northern Tamil Nadu is assumed to occur during the [[Reddy dynasty]] expansion till Kanchipuram areas.<ref name="Pollock2003">{{cite book|author=Sheldon I. Pollock|title=Literary cultures in history: reconstructions from South Asia|url=https://books.google.com/?id=ak9csfpY2WoC&pg=PA385&dq=origin+of+Reddy+kings#v=snippet&q=Reddy%20kings%20kondavidu%20addanki%20rajahmundry&f=false|accessdate=8 July 2011|year=2003|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=978-0-520-22821-4|pages=385–}}</ref>
==Origins==
Anavota Reddy (1335-1364 CE) of [[Reddy dynasty]] extended the dominion of the kingdom to Rajahmundry on the north, Kanchi on the south and Srisailam on the west. In a battle at Vallioor, Reddiapuram army defeated Travancore army in the 14th century.<ref name="-page 94 History of Travancore from the earliest times">{{cite book|last=Shungoonny Menon|first=P|title=History of Travancore from the earliest times|year=1998|publisher=Asian Educational Services|location=Madras|isbn=9788120601697|pages=523|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gxsrz7DAPxIC&source=gbs_navlinks_s}}</ref> In an information Board at the entrance of the Vallioor Murugan Temple it is stated that 14th century vallioor War - Reddiapuram army defeated Travancore Army at vallioor Battle. After this war Reddiyars settled at Samugarengapuram, Seelathikulam and all over Tirunelveli Region in the 14th century.{{citation needed|date=March 2016}}
[[File:Thiruppudaimaruthur Temple mural.jpg|thumb|right|Tamiraparani Battle]] A mural at the Tiruppudaimaruthur temple in Tirunelveli district in Tamil Nadu, shows the emissaries of the Vijayanagara king Achyutadeva Raya serving an ultimatum to the Travancore ruler Bhoothala Veera Udaya Marthanda Varma to pay tributes to him and return the Pandya territory to Sri Vallabhan. It also depicts the "Tamiraparani battle" between the armies of Achyutadeva Raya and Bhoothala Varma.<ref name="Tamiraparani battle between the armies of Achyutadeva Raya and Bhoothala Varma.">{{cite news|last=SUBRAMANIAN|first=T.S|title=Do Tamil Nadu temple murals portray Tamiraparani battle?|url=http://www.thehindu.com/arts/history-and-culture/article2440107.ece|accessdate=10 September 2011|newspaper=TheHindu|date=10 September 2011|location=Chennai, India}}</ref> They are believed moved into [[Tamil Nadu]] with the expansion of [[Vijayanagara Empire|Vijayanagar]] empire along with other Telugu and [[Kannada]] origin social groups. They have their origin in Vannipuranam.{{citation needed|date=March 2016}}
They migrated from Andhra Pradesh and Orissa to Tamil Nadu particularly to Madurai District at the period of Thirumalai Nayakkar rule.{{citation needed|date=March 2016}}
==Amongst the Tamil Sanjeeve Reddy diaspora== [[File:Kondavid-drug. Signed 'W.R.'.jpg|thumb|left|225px|Water colour painting - Kondavidu fort, Reddy Kingdom.]] Through emigration, there are now many Reddiars in the [[Tamil people|Tamil]] communities of United States, South Africa, Singapore, Australia, United Kingdom.{{citation needed|date=March 2016}}. The title does not generally mark the person as a Telugu but as an ethnic Tamil along with [[Naidu]] or Naidoo, [[Pillai (title)|Pillai]], [[Gounder]] and [[Chetty]] as surnames used in the [[Tamil diaspora]]. See distinction between Reddy and Reddiars.
==Current status== In India, Reddiars are classified as [[Forward caste]].<ref name="'Reddiar' is a forward community">{{cite book|title=Parliamentary Debates Official Report, Volume 208, Issues 5-6|date=2006|publisher=Council of States Secretariat, Indian Parliament Rajya Shaba|page=310|edition=1ST|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CQ0NAQAAMAAJ&q=reddiar+forward+community&dq=reddiar+forward+community&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwijstOBqMbTAhXL6iYKHTMcCCQQ6AEIJzAA|accessdate=28 April 2017}}</ref><ref name="Life as a Dalit: View from the Bottom UP">{{cite book|last1=Mencher|first1=Joan|title=Life as a Dalit: Views from the Bottom on Caste in India|date=2013|publisher=SAGE Publications India|isbn=9788132111238|page=88|edition=1ST}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YFF9BgAAQBAJ&pg=PA200&dq=the+politics+of+cultural+nationalism+in+south+india+reddiar&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjaydXMosbTAhVFRSYKHRdpAqkQ6AEIJzAA#v=onepage&q=the%20politics%20of%20cultural%20nationalism%20in%20south%20india%20reddiar&f=false|title=The Politics of Cultural Nationalism in South India|last=Barnett|first=Marguerite Ross|date=2015-03-08|publisher=Princeton University Press|isbn=9781400867189|language=en}}</ref><ref name="Indiana University Press">{{cite book|last1=Sreenivas|first1=Mytheli|title=Wives, Widows, and Concubines: The Conjugal Family Ideal in Colonial India|date=2008|publisher=Indiana University Press|isbn=9780253351180|page=144|edition=1ST|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zvf7zccTKTEC&pg=PA144&lpg=PA144&dq=reddiar+forward+community&source=bl&ots=44UtatxaGc&sig=TOns4ow0cXALJMAmYqGhwvvoTm4&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi9uqfOoMbTAhXITSYKHY1oAR0Q6AEIRTAH#v=onepage&q=reddiar%20forward%20community&f=false|accessdate=28 April 2017}}</ref><ref name="Always on the Reddy">{{cite web|title=Always on the Reddy|url=http://www.outlookindia.com/magazine/story/always-on-the-reddy/282339|publisher=Outlook|accessdate=28 April 2017}}</ref> In Tamil Nadu, Reddiars are classified as Forward Caste by the British.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Ross Barnett|first1=Marguerite|title=The Politics of Cultural Nationalism in South India|isbn=978-0691616865|page=49 |edition=1|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YFF9BgAAQBAJ&pg=PA49&lpg=PA49&dq=reddiar+forward+caste&source=bl&ots=iDXDhw6nZN&sig=nMjD4fZHVqUNEDQi0Lt4Z2v-LqQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiUsM6slbzTAhVIKCYKHVYjBr04ChDoAQgoMAE#v=onepage&q=reddiar%20forward%20caste&f=false|accessdate=24 April 2017}}</ref><ref name="Tamil Nadu elections">{{cite web |url=https://scroll.in/article/804887/whos-who-in-tamil-nadu-elections-kn-nehru |title=Who’s who in Tamil Nadu elections: KN Nehru |deadurl=no |accessdate=24 April 2017}}</ref> For example, the first chief minister of Tamil Nadu (Madras Presidency in 1920) was a Reddiar.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/A._Subbarayalu_Reddiar |title=A. Subbarayalu Reddiar |deadurl=no |accessdate=24 April 2017}}</ref>{{Better source|reason=per WP:CIRCULAR|date=November 2017}}<ref name="ChiefMinisters">{{cite web|title=Chief Ministers of Tamil Nadu since 1920|url=http://www.assembly.tn.gov.in/archive/list/cmlist.htm|website=Tamilnadu Legislative Assembly|publisher=Tamilnadu Legislative Assembly|accessdate=4 June 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.worldstatesmen.org/India_BrProvinces.htm|title=Provinces of British India|last=cahoon|first=ben|website=www.worldstatesmen.org|access-date=2018-05-25}}</ref> Today, Reddiars are generally classified as Forward Caste in Tamil Nadu.<ref name="'Reddiar' is a forward community"/><ref name="Life as a Dalit: View from the Bottom UP"/><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=YFF9BgAAQBAJ&pg=PA200&dq=the+politics+of+cultural+nationalism+in+south+india+reddiar&hl=en&sa=X&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=the%20politics%20of%20cultural%20nationalism%20in%20south%20india%20reddiar&f=false|title=The Politics of Cultural Nationalism in South India|last=Barnett|first=Marguerite Ross|date=2015-03-08|publisher=Princeton University Press|isbn=9781400867189|language=en}}</ref><ref name="Indiana University Press"/><ref name="Tamil Nadu elections"/><ref name="Chennai High Court">{{cite web|url=http://www.the-laws.com/Encyclopedia/Browse/Case?CaseId=215102213000|publisher=Chennai High Court|title = S. THARMARAJ Vs. THE UNION OF INDIA AND ORS.}}</ref> For example, a Member of Parliament in Rajya Sabha in 2006 distinguished between Reddiars who are generally classified as forward castes in Tamil Nadu and Koda Reddys who are classified as Scheduled Tribes in Tamil Nadu.<ref name="'Reddiar' is a forward community"/> Similarly, the Madras High Court in 2015 considered this distinction between Reddiars who are generally classified as forward castes and konda reddys who are classified as Scheduled Tribes as dispositive a writ petition in a reservation case in Tamil Nadu.<ref name="Chennai High Court"/> After Independence, some sub-castes among Reddiars in Tamil Nadu such a Ganjam Reddys have been included in the Backward Class list by the state government.<ref name="Ganjam Reddy">{{cite web|title=List of Backward Classes approved by Government of Tamil Nadu|url=http://www.bcmbcmw.tn.gov.in/bclist.htm|publisher=Tamil Nadu State Government|accessdate=28 April 2017}}</ref><ref name="Tamil Nadu elections"/> Some sub-castes like Ganjam Reddys from Tamil Nadu have now sought classification as backwards caste in the central government list.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/india/report-include-reddy-community-in-other-list-of-obcs-in-tamil-nadu-1804470|title = Include Reddy Community In Other Backward Communities}}</ref> Konda Reddys are classified as Scheduled Tribes.<ref>{{cite web|title=S. THARMARAJ Vs. THE UNION OF INDIA AND ORS.|url=http://www.the-laws.com/Encyclopedia/Browse/Case?CaseId=215102213000|publisher=Chennai High Court}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=THE CONSTITUTION (SCHEDULED TRIBES) ORDER (SECOND AMENDMENT) BILL, 2011|url=http://www.prsindia.org/uploads/media/Schedule%20Tribe%20Second%20Amendment/SCR%20Constitution%20ST%20Order%20second%20amendment%20Bill%202011.pdf|publisher=Indian Constitution Schedule Tribes Order|accessdate=28 April 2017|ref=Page 44}}</ref> Some reddiars are classified as Backward caste, in Kerala where they migrated to in early 1900 (excludes Malabar district where Reddiars are classified as forward).<ref>{{cite web|title=KERALA STATE & SUBORDINATE SERVICES RULES PART I SCHEDULE III- OTHER BACKWARD CLASSES IN THE KERALA STATE.|url=http://www.kscbc.kerala.gov.in/images/stories/obc_list.pdf|publisher=Kerala State|accessdate=4 June 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=LIST OF OTHER BACKWARD CLASSES IN KERALA STATE|url=https://www.keralapsc.gov.in/index.php?option=com_content&id=338&Itemid=198|publisher=Kerala Public Services Commission|accessdate=4 June 2017}}</ref> For example, Reddiars in Malabar excluding Ganjam Reddys are classified as forward.<ref>{{cite web|title=KERALA STATE & SUBORDINATE SERVICES RULES PART I SCHEDULE III- OTHER BACKWARD CLASSES IN THE KERALA STATE.|url=http://www.kscbc.kerala.gov.in/images/stories/obc_list.pdf|publisher=Kerala State|accessdate=4 June 2017}}</ref> Reddiars in other districts are classified as backward since 1993.<ref>{{cite web|title=KERALA STATE & SUBORDINATE SERVICES RULES PART I SCHEDULE III- OTHER BACKWARD CLASSES IN THE KERALA STATE.|url=http://www.kscbc.kerala.gov.in/images/stories/obc_list.pdf|publisher=Kerala State|accessdate=4 June 2017}}</ref> Some Reddiars in Kerala are considered protected minorities, who need better educational access due to merchantile roots of Reddiars in Kerala and lack of significant land ownership, except in Malabar district of Kerala.<ref>{{cite web|title=KERALA STATE & SUBORDINATE SERVICES RULES PART I SCHEDULE III- OTHER BACKWARD CLASSES IN THE KERALA STATE.|url=http://www.kscbc.kerala.gov.in/images/stories/obc_list.pdf|publisher=Kerala State|accessdate=4 June 2017}}</ref> There is a separate section of Reddiars called Konda Reddy who were considered Shudras in British surveys, who follow tribal customs.<ref name="Chennai High Court"/><ref name="'Reddiar' is a forward community"/> Recently, Konda Reddys in Odissa have been pressing for inclusion in the Scheduled Tribes list.<ref name="Konda Reddys in Orissa">{{cite web|title=ST status plea for Konda Reddys|url=https://www.telegraphindia.com/1130626/jsp/odisha/story_17046580.jsp#.WQLQP1Btnxs|website=The Telegraph|accessdate=28 April 2017}}</ref>
==Reddy versus Reddiars==
Though The Origin is thought tobe same with little arguments, Reddys predominantly speak Telugu and follow Telugu cultural festivals like [[Ugadi]] and follow all other Andhra norms. Whereas Reddiars who came to the Tamil region speak both Tamil for business and Telugu at home and identify and follow Telugu cultural norms. They also celebrate [[Pongal|Thai Pongal]], Tamil [[New Year]] and Ugadi. For survival and to maintain their Dravidian lineage, they are active in supporting local Temple societies and local political aspirations. Some have become very prominent in [[Dravidian Nationalism|Dravidian nationalistic]] causes and are represented in Tamil literary circles as great patrons and scholars of Tamil language.
==Prominent Reddiars== * [[A. Subbarayalu Reddiar]] - First Chief Minister of Madras Presidency - Dec 1920 - June 1921 * [[V. Venkatasubha Reddiar]] - Former Chief Minister of Puducherry and a prominent [[Puducherry]] freedom fighter<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hinduonnet.com/2005/06/07/stories/2005060704130300.htm|title=The Hindu : Other States / Pondicherry News : Venkatasubba Reddiar remembered|website=www.hinduonnet.com|access-date=2018-05-25}}</ref> * [[O. P. Ramaswamy Reddiyar]] - Chief Minister of Madras Presidency - 1947-1949 * [[Vaithilingam]] - Chief Minister of Puducherry - July 4, 1991 to May 13, 1996 (first term), September 4, 2008 – April 13, 2011 * [[Annamalai Reddiyar]] - Tamil poet * [[K. K. S. S. R. Ramachandran]] Former Co-operation, PWD minister in MGR cabinet.{{citation needed|date=March 2016}} * [[K. N. Nehru]] :Former Milk, food minister in DMK cabinet(1996–2000). Transport minister in DMK cabinet (2006–2011){{citation needed|date=March 2016}} * [[Napoleon (actor)|Napoleon]]: Actor and [[Member of Parliament|MP]] of [[Perambalur (Lok Sabha constituency)|Perambalur Constituency]] Central Minister Of State for Social Justice and Empowerment{{citation needed|date=March 2016}} * [[ G. R. Vaishnav]] Indian volleyball player
